  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I watch YouTube videos on a VLC media player?",
  "response": "You can watch YouTube videos on VLC Media Player by following these steps:\n\n### Method 1: Using a YouTube Video URL\n\n1. **Open VLC Media Player:** Launch the VLC application on your device.\n\n2. **Get the YouTube Video URL:**\n   - Go to YouTube, find the video you want to watch, and copy its URL from the address bar. The URL will look something like this: `https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XXXXXXXXX`.\n\n3. **Open the Network Stream:**\n   - In VLC, click on `Media` in the top menu.\n   - Select `Open Network Stream` (or press `Ctrl + N` on Windows or `Command + N` on macOS).\n\n4. **Paste the URL:**\n   - In the dialog box that appears, paste the copied YouTube video URL into the provided field.\n\n5. **Play the Video:**\n   - Click on the `Play` button. VLC will now stream the YouTube video.\n\n### Method 2: Using the YouTube Playlist\n\nIf you have multiple YouTube videos to play:\n\n1. **Create a Playlist:**\n   - Similar to the steps above, gather the URLs of all the videos you want to watch.\n\n2. **Open VLC:**\n   - Launch VLC Media Player.\n\n3. **Open the Playlist:**\n   - Go to `Media`, then `Open Network Stream`.\n   - In the dialog box, paste each URL one by one and ensure each URL is on a new line.\n\n4. **Play the Playlist:**\n   - Click on `Play` and VLC will begin streaming each video in the playlist.\n\n### Important Notes\n\n- **YouTube Video Availability:** Sometimes, videos may be restricted or unavailable due to copyright issues, which can prevent VLC from streaming them.\n  \n- **Internet Connection:** Make sure you have a stable internet connection, as VLC streams videos directly from YouTube.\n\n- **VLC Updates:** Ensure that you are using the latest version of VLC Media Player, as older versions may have issues with streaming.\n\nBy following these methods, you should be able to watch YouTube videos directly using VLC Media Player!",
